<caption><h2>Table Notes:</h2></caption>
       <tr>
       <th colspan="2"><h4>colspan:</h4></th>
       </tr>
       <tr>
      <td colspan="2"> Specifies the number of cells you want that column to span (cover) <br>
         Possible values: positive integer number
          </td>
         </tr>
        <tr>
       <th colespan="2"><h4>rowspan:</h4></th> 	
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th colspan="2">
            Specifies the number of cells you want the row to span (cover)
            Possible values: positive integer number
             </td>
         </tr>
            <tr>
        <td colspan="2"><h4>scope:</h4></td> 
              Specifies if a header cell is the header for a row, column, rowgroup or colgroup 
              <br>Possible values: row, col, rowgroup, colgroup, auto 
              
   
    </tr>
    <br>If the scope attribute is not specified, then browsers automatically select the set of cells to which the header cell applies.</br>
      </caption>
    </table>

<h3>&lt;tr&gt; </h3> Creates a table row.
<br>

<h3>&lt;th&gt;</h3> There are two types of cells in a table - header and standard. &lt;th&gt; creates table header cells. The content of table header cells is bold and centered by default.
<br>
<h3>&lt;td&gt;</h3>  The <>td> element defines a cell of a table that contains data. Content of table data cells is left-aligned by default.

<p>
  Now, let's have a look at the &lt;colgroup&gt; and &lt;col&gt; tags <br>
   <h3>&lt;colgroup&gt;</h3>
This element allows you to group columns in a table. Grouping columns is useful if you want to specify properties for a group of columns, like applying styles to the whole column instead of repeating it for each cell. 

<br>

<br>Attribute: span - takes a positive integer value.   Essentially it allows a single cell to stretch to cover multiple columns on a particular row 
  </br>
    <BR>
      <h3>&lt;col></h3>
Used within &lt;colgroup>, the &lt;col&gt; element specifies the column for each column within a colgroup. The only element a &lt;colgroup&gt; can contain is &lt;col&gt;. 
</BR>
Attribute:

span - takes a positive integer value. It specifies the number of columns you want the col element to span (cover). </p>
<p>
  <h3>&lt;thead</h3>
The &lt;thead> element represents the block of rows that consist of the column labels (headers) for the parent table element.
<br>
<h3>&lt;tbody></h3>
Following &lt;thead>, subsequent rows are considered body rows in a table. Best practice is to encode them using a &lt;tbody&gt; element. <br> The &lt;tbody&gt; element encapsulates a set of table rows (&lt;tr&gt; elements), indicating that they comprise the body of the table (&lt;table&gt;).</br>
<h3>&lt;tfoot></h3>
The footer is the last table part to be specified. Rows within &lt;tfoot> are defined to be footer rows for the table
</p>


